In this example, we use the `article` document class and include the `tocdepth` package to control the depth of the table of contents (TOC).

We set the depth of the TOC to `subsection` using the `\settocdepth` command, which means that the TOC will include sections and subsections, but not subsubsections.

The `\tableofcontents` command is used to generate the TOC. LaTeX will automatically create a table of contents based on the sectioning commands (`\section`, `\subsection`, etc.) used in the document.

When you compile this document, LaTeX will generate a table of contents that looks like this:

